|8th}}\n| {{nom|8th}}\n| {{nom|7th}}\n|{{won|'''W (4th)'''|color=lime}}\n| {{nom|8th}}\n| {{nom|6th}}\n| {{nom|6th}}\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|CF (5th)\n|}\n\n'''Notes''':\n* W = Winner; \n* R = Runner-up; \n* SF = Semifinalist; \n* EF = Eliminated in \"The Eliminator\" Final (4th vs 5th) (from 2020); \n* KO = Knocked-out in \"The Knock-Out\" Final (3rd vs winner of the Eliminator) (from 2020); \n* CF = Eliminated in \"The Challenger\" Final (2nd vs winner of the Knock-Out) (from 2020);\n* TBD = To be Decided;\n<!-- DNP = Did Not Play; -->\n* (x) = End of league games table position;\n\n==Sponsorship==\n'''Title Sponsor'''\n* [[KFC]]\n* [[Rebel (company)|Rebel]] ([[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]])\n\n'''Associate Sponsor'''\n* [[Weet-Bix]]\n* [[Toyota]]\n* [[Extra (gum)|Wrigley Extra]]\n* [[Commonwealth Bank]]\n* [[Balkrishna Industries|BKT Tires]]\n* [[Woolworths Supermarkets|Woolworths]]\n* [[Dream11]]\n\n'''Apparel Sponsor'''\n* [[Majestic Athletic]] (Team Apparel)\n* [['47 (brand)|'47]] (Caps/Hats)\n\n'''Broadcast Partners'''\n* [[Fox Cricket]]\n* [[Seven Network]]\n* [[Radio Australia]] (Outside Australia)\n* [[Macquarie Sports Radio 954|Macquarie Sports Radio]]\n* [[Crocmedia]] ([[1116 SEN]])\n\n==Salary cap==\n\n[[File:Big Bash League Logo.svg|thumb|BBL old logo used up to 2014\u201315 season|150px]]\nThe salary cap was initially $1 million, and increased to $1.05 million for the third season.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-tweaks-player-rules-20130612-2o3am.html Big Bash tweaks player rules] smh.com.au. Retrieved on 3 December 2015.</ref> In February 2015, the salary cap increased to $1.3 million for the fifth season,<ref name=\"cricketbadger1\"/> and to $1.6 million for the sixth season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-kfc-bbl-squads-playing-list-salary-cap-guidelines-updated-bbl07/2017-08-09 |title=Updated BBL07 squads for each team |publisher=Cricket Australia |author=Kanoniukm, Callum |date=9 August 2017 |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Prize money==\n[[Cricket Australia]] increased the prize money for the BBL to a total of $890,000 for the four finalists from [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316 season]], after the [[Champions League Twenty20]] tournament was discontinued with effect from 2015. The prize money will be split between the teams as follows:<ref name=\"prize money\">[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/cricket-australia-increase-big-bash-league-prize-money-after-no-clt20/2015-12-15 CA INCREASE BBL|05 PRIZE POOL] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 15 December 2015</ref>\n\n*$20,000 \u2013 To the team finishing fifth in the season\n*$80,000 \u2013 To each losing semi-finalist\n*$260,000 \u2013 To the [[#Tournament_results|Runner up]] \n*$450,000 \u2013 To the [[#Tournament_results|Champion]] of the season\n\nHowever, the additional cash increase of $600,000 will go to successful clubs and not their players. Up to the [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 BBL season]], a total prize money of $290,000 was awarded.<ref name=\"prize money\" />\n\n==Audience==\n\n===Attendance===\n[[File:Melbourne Stars vs Hobart Hurricanes, BBL 05.jpg|thumb|240px|Melbourne Stars vs Hobart Hurricanes at the MCG on 6 January 2016]]\nAverage home crowds for the regular season are listed below. These figures do not include finals matches. The figures for the whole season average include the finals.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash-league-infant-tournament-now-part-of-australian-crickets-summer-fabric/news-story/98897cf3111da3cb16f6fd9e6744e101 Big Bash League: Infant tournament now part of Australian cricket's summer fabric] heraldsun.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.adelaidestrikers.com.au/news/crowd-records-tumble-at-strikers-semi-final/2015-01-25 Crowd Records Tumble at Strikers Semi-Final], adelaidestrikers.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref> Post-Christmas matches have historically been the highest attended period for the League.<ref name=\"BBL5 schedule\">[http://www.cricket.com.au/news/bbl05-big-bash-league-fixture-release-2015-16-final-host-highest-qualifying-team-all-matches-live/2015-07-12 Big Bash League schedule released] cricket.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref> BBL has provided a platform to create interest in playing cricket among younger children, due to its big hitting, high scoring and entertaining nature of the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-12-22/hinds:-even-test-purists-must-see-the-bright-side-of-the-bbl/9278950 |title=Big Bash League winning over Test cricket purists as kids embrace the game |author=Hinds, Richard |date=22 December 2017 |publisher=ABC News |accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 season]] saw record domestic cricket crowds in the states of [[South Australia]], [[New South Wales]], [[Tasmania]] and the [[Australian Capital Territory|ACT]], including a record attendance of 52,633 at the [[Adelaide Strikers]]' home semi-final, which was then the biggest ever crowd at the redeveloped [[Adelaide Oval]].<ref name=\"BBL5 schedule\" />\n\nIn the [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316 season]], attendance figure records continued to be broken across all the venues. [[Perth Scorchers]] became the first ever BBL team to sell out all of its home matches in a season.<ref>[http://www.perthscorchers.com.au/news/scorchers-set-league-sellout-record/2015-12-31 Scorchers Set League Sell-Out Record], perthscorchers.com.au. Retrieved on 12 January 2016</ref> On 2 January 2016, the BBL single match attendance record was surpassed, with a crowd of 80,883 watching the first of two Melbourne derbies between the [[Melbourne Stars]] and the [[Melbourne Renegades]] at the [[Melbourne Cricket Ground]]. The Big Bash League also entered the top 10 most attended sports leagues in the world with respect to average crowd per match in this season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.firstpost.com/sports/big-bash-league-2016-17-smashes-viewership-records-exceeds-expectations-3225952.html |title=Big Bash League 2016\u201317 smashes viewership records, exceeds expectations |work=Firstpost |date=29 January 2017 |accessdate=17 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Team\n! colspan=9 | Crowd average\n|-\n! [[2011\u201312 Big Bash League season|2011\u201312]]\n! [[2012\u201313 Big Bash League season|2012\u201313]]\n! [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season|2013\u201314]]\n! [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315]]\n! [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|2015\u201316]]\n! [[2016\u201317 Big Bash League season|2016\u201317]]\n! [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|2017\u201318]]\n! [[2018\u201319 Big Bash League season|2018\u201319]]\n! [[2019\u201320 Big Bash League season|2019\u201320]]\n|-\n|align=left| [[Adelaide Strikers]]\n| 21,986\n| 13,319\n| 23,703\n| 36,023\n| 42,437\n| 41,275\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at Traeger Park in Alice Springs where the attendance was 3,906, 27 January 2018, etc.</ref> 33,951\n| 28,095\n| 25,139\n|-\n|align=left| [[Brisbane Heat]]\n| 17,072\n| 15,897\n| 23,685\n| 24,611\n| 29,353\n| 34,190\n| 32,980\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast.</ref> 22,343\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast.</ref> 23,167\n|-\n|align=left| [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n| 10,517\n| 12,107\n| 9,552\n| 13,776\n| 16,640\n| 17,570\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at UTAS Stadium in Launceston where the attendance was 16,734, 27 January 2018, etc.</ref> 13,536\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at UTAS Stadium in Launceston.</ref> 11,197\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at TIO Traeger Park and UTAS Stadium respectively.</ref>  8,298\n|-\n|align=left| [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| 13,324\n| 13,184\n| 21,929\n| 22,324\n| 29,010\n| 30,033\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at Kardinia Park in Geelong where the attendance was 23,586, 27 January 2018, etc.</ref> 28,315\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Kardinia Park in Geelong.</ref> 19,881\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Kardinia Park in Geelong.</ref> 15,528\n|- \n|align=left| [[Melbourne Stars]]\n| 27,424\n| 21,451\n| 21,813\n| 27,698\n| 40,986\n| 49,578\n| 31,628\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games, one of which was played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast and the other one at Ted Summerton Reserve in Moe.</ref> 21,541\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games, one of which was played at Metricon Stadium in Gold Coast and the other one at Ted Summerton Reserve in Moe.</ref> 21,447\n|- \n|align=left| [[Perth Scorchers]]\n| 14,905\n| 11,539\n| 17,380\n| 18,825\n| 20,273\n| 20,567\n| 21,511\n| 30,133\n| 26,586\n|- \n|align=left| [[Sydney Sixers]]\n| 20,068\n| 13,286\n| 19,914\n| 23,849\n| 27,956\n| 30,368\n| 24,815\n| 17,784\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at C.ex Coffs International Stadium in Coffs Harbour.</ref> 15,327\n|-\n|align=left| [[Sydney Thunder]]\n| 18,423\n| 10,278\n| 14,866\n| 17,938\n| 19,333\n| 20,688\n| <ref>Includes one regular season home game played at Manuka Oval in Canberra where the attendance was 11,319, 27 January 2018, etc.</ref> 15,432\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Manuka Oval in Canberra.</ref> 12,461\n| <ref>Includes two regular season home games played at Manuka Oval in Canberra.</ref> 10,888\n|-\n|align=left| ''Finals''\n| 15,222\n| 17,568\n| 15,286\n| 27,920\n| 42,182\n| 25,642\n| 43,330\n| 22,854\n| 12,691\n|-\n| align=center|'''Whole season'''\n| '''18,021'''\n| '''14,883'''\n| '''18,778'''\n| '''23,590'''\n| '''29,443'''\n| '''30,114'''\n| '''26,531'''\n| '''20,552'''\n| '''18,353'''\n|}\n\n'''Notes'''\n\n===Television===\n\n====Australian television====\nBBL games are currently broadcast in Australia on free-to-air television by the [[Seven Network]] and subscription television by [[Fox Cricket]]. The [[Seven Network]] broadcasts 45 of 61 Matches including the Finals Series. [[Fox Cricket]] televises all 61 Matches including 16 Matches exclusively in 4K.<ref name=\"cricket 2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theroar.com.au/2018/04/13/foxtel-snatch-cricket-rights-from-nine-end-of-an-era/|title=End of an era confirmed: Foxtel and Seven snatch cricket rights from Nine|publisher=The Roar|first=Scott|last=Bailey|date=13 April 2018|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe rights were previously held by [[Network Ten|Network 10]], who in 2013 paid $100 million for BBL rights over five years, marking the channel's first foray in elite cricket coverage.<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/cricket/new-big-bash-league-broadcaster-channel-ten-thrilled-with-ratings-for-season-opening-derby/story-fni2usfi-1226788040468 New Big Bash League broadcaster Channel Ten thrilled with ratings for season opening derby] heraldsun.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015.</ref>\n\nNetwork 10's BBL coverage became a regular feature of Australian summers and attracted an average audience of more than 943,000 people nationally in 2014\u201315 season, including a peak audience of 1.9 million viewers for the final between the Scorchers and Sixers.<ref>[http://www.cricket.com.au/news/bbl05-big-bash-league-fixture-release-2015-16-final-host-highest-qualifying-team-all-matches-live/2015-07-12 Big Bash League schedule released] cricket.com.au. Retrieved on 25 November 2015</ref>\n\nThe 2015\u201316 season attracted an average audience of 1.13 million for each match in Australia this season, an 18% increase on the previous season. A [[Audience measurement#GRPs/TRPs|cumulative audience]] of 9.65 million watched the matches in Australia, out of which 39% were females.<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/kfc-big-bash-league-reaches-new-heights-in-bbl05-wbbl01-womens-big-bash/~/media/4AA18022BED84381B18846753425BC84.ashx Season Wrap \u2013 BBL|05] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/kfc-big-bash-league-reaches-new-heights-in-bbl05-wbbl01-womens-big-bash/2016-01-25 BBL AND WBBL SOAR TO NEW HIGHS] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref> The opening Sydney Derby match of the [[2015\u201316 Big Bash League season|season]] attracted a peak audience of 1.53 million.<ref>[http://www.bigbash.com.au/news/big-bash-league-tv-ratings-bbl-sydney-sixers-sydney-thunder/2015-12-18 #SydneySmash breaks ratings record] bigbash.com.au. Retrieved on 19 December 2015</ref> The last group match between [[Melbourne Renegades|Renegades]] and [[Adelaide Strikers|Strikers]] in Session 2 was watched by an average audience of 1.36 million, which peaked at 1.67 million.<ref>[https://twitter.com/malcolmconn/status/689335385575403520 Session 2: 1.36 mil Peak 1.67 mil Audience up 41% on 2014\u201315 Session 2 ave #BBL05] ''Malcolm Conn \u2013 Commercial Manager, Cricket Australia.'' Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref> The BBL Final was watched by an average audience of 1.79 million, which peaked at 2.24 million viewers. This was the first time that the ratings for a BBL match crossed the 2 million mark.<ref>[https://twitter.com/malcolmconn/status/691391474928209920 SBIG ratings for BIG #BBL05 #BBLFinal! 1.79 mil watched @ThunderBBL win their first title. Peak 2.24 mil Audience up 17% 2015 final session 2] ''Malcolm Conn \u2013 Commercial Manager, Cricket Australia.'' Retrieved on 25 January 2016</ref>\n\n====Broadcast partners====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Countries \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width: auto; color:#E4F300; background:#181A04;\" | Network/s\n|-\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Australia]]\n|[[Fox Cricket]] (2011\u201313, 2018\u2013present)<br />[[Network Ten]] (2013\u20132018)<br />[[Seven Network]] (2018\u2013present)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[New Zealand]]\n|[[Sky Sport (New Zealand)|Sky Sport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|PAK}} [[Pakistan]]\n| [[PTV Sports]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]]\n|[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| [[Sony ESPN]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|SRI}} [[Sri Lanka]]\n| [[Sony Six|Sony SIX]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[United Kingdom]]\n| [[BT Sport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[United States]]\n| [[Willow (TV channel)|Willow]] (2018\u2013present)<br />[[NBC Sports Gold]] (2018\u2013present)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Canada]]\n| [[Commonwealth Broadcasting Network|CBN]] & [[ATN Cricket Plus]]</small><ref>{{cite press release|title=ATN Acquires Exclusive Canadian Broadcast Rights for Cricket from around the World|publisher=CNW|date=25 July 2016|url=http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/atn-acquires-exclusive-canadian-broadcast-rights-for-cricket-from-around-the-world-588147782.html|accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[South Africa]]\n| [[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|Supersport]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|PNG}} [[Papua New Guinea]]\n| [[National Broadcasting Corporation of Papua New Guinea|NBC Papua New Guinea]]\n|-\n| South-East Asia\n| [[Fox Sports Asia]]\n|-\n| Central Asia\n|[[Sony Pictures Sports Network|SPN Sports India]]\n|-\n| Africa\n| [[Kwese Sports]]\n|-\n| The West Indies\n| [[Sports Max]]<br />[[Flow Sports]]\n|}\n\n==Grounds==\n{{See also|List of Big Bash League venues}}\nA total of seventeen grounds have been used to host BBL matches to date. [[Sydney Thunder]] moved out of [[ANZ Stadium]] after [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 season]] and relocated to [[Sydney Showground Stadium]] for the next 10 years. From 2020, the tournament Final is played at the home ground of the team which wins 'The Qualifier', a finals match contested between the teams finishing 1st and 2nd in the League. The [[WACA Ground]] has hosted the final four times, more than any other venue. [[Manuka Oval]] hosted the final of [[2014\u201315 Big Bash League season|2014\u201315 BBL season]] as a [[neutral venue]] primarily because other major grounds were being prepared for the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]].<ref name=\"Manuka Oval venue\">[http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash/big-bash-league-final-at-manuka-oval-disappointing-for-perth-scorchers-fans-20150126-12y8ta.html Big Bash League final at Manuka Oval \"disappointing\" for Perth Scorchers fans] smh.com.au. Retrieved on 2 December 2015</ref>\n\n[[Optus Stadium]] replaced the WACA Ground as the home ground of [[Perth Scorchers]] commencing from the [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|2017\u201318 BBL]] semi-finals, where [[Perth]]'s home match against [[Hobart Hurricanes]] (and a doubleheader [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] match featuring the [[Perth Scorchers (WBBL)|Perth Scorchers]] and [[Sydney Thunder (WBBL)|Sydney Thunder]]) became only the second public event at the new [[stadium]].\n\nIn September 2017 the [[Adelaide Strikers]] agreed to play one home BBL and [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] match at [[Traeger Park]] in [[Alice Springs]] over the course of the 2017\u201318 season. In 2018, they announced that one BBL and two [[Women's Big Bash League|WBBL]] matches would be held at [[Traeger Park]] for the [[2018\u201319 Big Bash League season|2018\u201319]] and [[2019\u201320 Big Bash League season|2019\u201320]] seasons. Since [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|2017\u201318]], the [[Melbourne Renegades]] have played two matches per season at [[Kardinia Park]] in [[Geelong]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and the [[Hobart Hurricanes]] play multiple games at [[University of Tasmania Stadium|UTAS Stadium]] in [[Launceston, Tasmania|Launceston]], [[Tasmania]].\n\n{{wide image|Panoramic SCG BBL.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|Panoramic view of the SCG during a Big Bash League match in 2011. It is the home ground of Sydney Sixers.}}\n\n