{"title_page": "NHSX", "text_new": "'''NHSX''' is a [[United Kingdom Government]] unit with responsibility for setting national policy and developing best practice for [[National Health Service]] (NHS) technology, digital and data, including [[data sharing]] and transparency.<ref name=gov>{{cite web |title=NHSX: new joint organisation for digital, data and technology |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nhsx-new-joint-organisation-for-digital-data-and-technology |website=GOV.UK |language=en |date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was established in early 2019 by the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], to bring together information technology teams from the [[Department of Health and Social Care]], [[NHS England]], and [[NHS Improvement]]. NHSX will work closely with the [[Government Digital Service]] and other relevant government functions.<ref name=gov /> It is led by [[Matthew Gould]].<ref name=bbhc>{{cite news |title=Specialist unit will lead NHS digital revolution |url=https://www.buildingbetterhealthcare.co.uk/news/article_page/Specialist_unit_will_lead_NHS_digital_revolution/153614/cn164706 |accessdate=20 May 2019 |publisher=Building better Healthcare |date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The 'X' in NHSX stands for \"[[user experience]]\".<ref name=bbhc/>\n\nIn May 2019, Hancock announced plans to upgrade all hospitals, [[General practitioner|GP]] practices and community care services to full fibre connectivity, which is intended to enable more video consultations and improve the speed of access to clinical information.<ref>{{cite news |title=NHS hospitals and GP practices to get fibre optic internet |url=https://www.buildingbetterhealthcare.co.uk/news/article_page/NHS_hospitals_and_GP_practices_to_get_fibre_optic_internet/154373%20/cn164706 |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=Building Better Healthcare |date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech delivered on 12 June 2019, [[Nicola Blackwood|Baroness Blackwood]], Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Department of Health and Social Care, identified three delivery priorities for NHSX, which are \"focused on how we can make things better for patients and staff as soon as possible\". These priorities are:\n\n*cutting the amount of time that clinicians spend inputting and accessing data in NHS systems\n*making it easier for patients to access key NHS services on a [[smartphone]]\n*ensuring that essential diagnostic information can be accessed safely and reliably, from wherever a patient may be within the NHS.\n\nUnderlying these delivery priorities, she also noted that the technical priority for NHSX is the creation of a data-driven ecosystem.<ref>Blackwood, N., [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/embracing-ai-and-technology-to-improve-patient-outcomes Embracing AI and technology to improve patient outcomes], CogX Festival, GOV.UK, published 12 June 2019, accessed 24 June 2019</ref> It was announced in January 2020 that \u00a340 million was to be dedicated to improving login times for staff, using [[single sign-on]] technology.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tech chiefs pledge \u00a340m to end staff\u2019s \u2018ridiculous\u2019 login problems |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/tech-chiefs-pledge-40m-to-end-staffs-ridiculous-login-problems/7026633.article? |accessdate=24 February 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of the functions of the organisation is to manage the sharing of NHS patient data with industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=NHSX to oversee industry access to patient data |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/nhsx-to-oversee-industry-access-to-patient-data/7025560.article |accessdate=25 August 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Paperless NHS==\n\nIn June 2019 Gould admitted that the target of a paperless NHS by 2024 would be \"a stretch\". <ref>{{cite news |title=Paperless 2024 target a 'stretch' \u2013 NHSX CEO |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/paperless-2024-target-a-stretch-nhsx-ceo/7025445.article? |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=1 July 2019}}</ref>  The target, first announced in 2013, has repeatedly been moved back from 2018, 2020, and 2023.<ref>{{cite news |title=The digital challenge: achieving a paperless NHS by 2020 |url=https://www.healtheuropa.eu/paperless-nhs/88487/ |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Health Europa |date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website}}\n\n[[Category:National Health Service]]\n[[Category:Information technology organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "'''NHSX''' is a [[United Kingdom Government]] unit with responsibility for setting national policy and developing best practice for [[National Health Service]] (NHS) technology, digital and data - including [[data sharing]] and transparency.<ref name=gov>{{cite web |title=NHSX: new joint organisation for digital, data and technology |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/nhsx-new-joint-organisation-for-digital-data-and-technology |website=GOV.UK |language=en |date=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt was established in early 2019 by the [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], [[Matt Hancock]], to bring together the technology leadership from the [[Department of Health and Social Care]], [[NHS England]], and [[NHS Improvement]]. NHSX will work closely with the [[Government Digital Service]] and other relevant government functions.<ref name=gov /> It is led by [[Matthew Gould]].<ref name=bbhc>{{cite news |title=Specialist unit will lead NHS digital revolution |url=https://www.buildingbetterhealthcare.co.uk/news/article_page/Specialist_unit_will_lead_NHS_digital_revolution/153614/cn164706 |accessdate=20 May 2019 |publisher=Building better Healthcare |date=9 April 2019}}</ref> The 'X' in NHSX stands for \"[[user experience]]\".<ref name=bbhc/>\n\nIn May 2019 Matt Hancock, announced plans to upgrade all hospitals, GP practices and community care services to full fibre connectivity, which is intended to enable more video consultations and improve the speed of access to clinical information.<ref>{{cite news |title=NHS hospitals and GP practices to get fibre optic internet |url=https://www.buildingbetterhealthcare.co.uk/news/article_page/NHS_hospitals_and_GP_practices_to_get_fibre_optic_internet/154373%20/cn164706 |accessdate=7 July 2019 |publisher=Building Better Healthcare |date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a speech delivered on 12 June 2019, [[Nicola Blackwood|Baroness Blackwood]], Parliamentary Under Secretary of State at the Department of Health and Social Care, identified three delivery priorities for NHSX, which are \"focused on how we can make things better for patients and staff as soon as possible\". These priorities are:\n\n*cutting the amount of time that clinicians spend inputting and accessing data in NHS systems\n*making it easier for patients to access key NHS services on a [[smartphone]]\n*ensuring that essential diagnostic information can be accessed safely and reliably, from wherever a patient may be within the NHS.\n\nUnderlying these delivery priorities, she also noted that the technical priority for NHSX is the creation of a data-driven ecosystem.<ref>Blackwood, N., [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/embracing-ai-and-technology-to-improve-patient-outcomes Embracing AI and technology to improve patient outcomes], CogX Festival, GOV.UK, published 12 June 2019, accessed 24 June 2019</ref> It was announced in January 2020 that \u00a340 million was to be dedicated to improving login times for staff with single sign-on technology.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tech chiefs pledge \u00a340m to end staff\u2019s \u2018ridiculous\u2019 login problems |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/tech-chiefs-pledge-40m-to-end-staffs-ridiculous-login-problems/7026633.article? |accessdate=24 February 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=4 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOne of the functions of the organisation is to manage the sharing of NHS patient data with industry.<ref>{{cite news |title=NHSX to oversee industry access to patient data |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/nhsx-to-oversee-industry-access-to-patient-data/7025560.article |accessdate=25 August 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Paperless NHS==\n\nIn June 2019 Gould admitted that the target of a paperless NHS by 2024 would be \"a stretch\". <ref>{{cite news |title=Paperless 2024 target a 'stretch' \u2013 NHSX CEO |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/technology-and-innovation/paperless-2024-target-a-stretch-nhsx-ceo/7025445.article? |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=1 July 2019}}</ref>  The target, first announced in 2013 has repeatedly been moved back from 2018, 2020, and 2023.<ref>{{cite news |title=The digital challenge: achieving a paperless NHS by 2020 |url=https://www.healtheuropa.eu/paperless-nhs/88487/ |accessdate=23 August 2019 |publisher=Health Europa |date=15 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n\n* [https://www.nhsx.nhs.uk/ NHSX's website]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:National Health Service]]\n[[Category:Information technology organisations based in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Wire723", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor copyedit, official website from Wikidata", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NHSX"}
{"title_page": "Zhangye National Geopark", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Zhangye National Geopark<br/>{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u6396\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed}}}}\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = File:Linze, Zhangye, Gansu, China - panoramio (4).jpg\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = Badlands of the Zhangye National Geopark\n| photo_width = \n| map = China Gansu\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| map_width = \n| relief =\n| location = [[Linze County]] and [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan County]]\n| nearest_city = [[Zhangye]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|38|54|55.98|N|100|7|59.52|E|region:CN-62|display=inline, title}}\n| area = {{convert|322|km2|abbr=on}}\n| established = December 27, 2005 (as provincial geopark)\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = \n| website = \n}}\n\nThe '''Zhangye National Geopark ''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u6396\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed |t=\u5f35\u6396\u570b\u5bb6\u5730\u8cea\u516c\u5712 |p=Zh\u0101ngy\u00e8 Gu\u00f3ji\u0101 D\u00eczh\u00ecg\u014dngyu\u00e1n}}) is located in [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan]] and [[Linze]] counties within the prefecture-level city of [[Zhangye]], in [[Gansu]], China.  It covers an area of {{convert|322|km2}}.  The site became a quasi-national geopark on April 23, 2012 (provisional name: '''Zhangye Danxia Geopark''').  It was formally designated as \"Zhangye National Geopark\" by the Ministry of Land and Resources on June 16, 2016 after it has passed the on-site acceptance test.  Known for its colorful rock formations, it has been voted by Chinese media outlets as one of the most beautiful landforms in China.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Striated rocks in Zhangye National Geopark.jpg|thumb|left|Layers in the geopark]]\nThe park is located in the northern foothills of the [[Qilian Mountains]], in the counties of [[Linze County|Linze]] and [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan]], which are under the administration of the [[prefecture-level city]] of Zhangye, Gansu province. The main areas of [[Danxia landform]] are in Kangle and Baiyin townships.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}}\n\nThe core area of the park, Linze Danxia Scenic Area, is located {{convert|30|km}} west of downtown Zhangye and {{convert|20|km}} south of the seat of Linze County. It is the most developed and most visited part of the park.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}} A second scenic area, Binggou ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51b0\u6c9f}}), located on the north bank of Liyuan River ({{lang|zh-hans|\u68a8\u56ed\u6cb3}}), was officially inaugurated on 3 August 2014.{{sfn|Yong|2014}} Binggou covers an area of {{convert|300|km2}}, and its elevation ranges from 1,500 to 2,500 meters above sea level.{{sfn|Yong|2014}} A third area, Sunan Danxia Scenic Area, is located in Ganjun, south of Linze.\n\n==Landscape==\n[[File:Colorful strata (Zhangye National Geopark).jpg|thumb|right|Landscape of Zhangye National Geopark]]\nZhangye Danxia is known for the unusual colours of the rocks, which are smooth, sharp and several hundred meters tall. They are the result of deposits of [[sandstone]] and other minerals that occurred over 24 million years. The result (similar to a [[layer cake]]), was tilted by the action of the same tectonic plates responsible for creating parts of the [[Himalayan mountains]]. Wind, rain, and time then sculpted extraordinary shapes, including towers, pillars, and ravines, with varying colours, patterns, and sizes.{{sfn|Chapple|Rex|2014}}\n\n==Media and tourism==\nIn 2005, Zhangye Danxia was voted by a panel of reporters from 34 major media outlets as one of the most beautiful Danxia landform areas in China. In 2009, ''[[Chinese National Geography]]'' magazine chose Zhangye Danxia as one of the \"six most beautiful landforms\" in China.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}} The area has become a top tourist attraction for Zhangye. A series of boardwalks and access roads have been built to help visitors to explore the rock formations.{{sfn|Chapple|Rex|2014}} In 2014, 100 million yuan was invested to improve the facilities in the Binggou area.{{sfn|Yong|2014}}\n\nZhangye Danxia is '''featured''' as a natural wonder in the video game Sid Meier\u2019s [[Civilization VI]]. It was added in the Rise and Fall expansion.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"230px\">\nBuildings in Zhangye National Geopark.jpg\nFlickr image 29851221553.jpg\nFlickr image 30483606125.jpg\nColourful mountains of the Zhangye National Geopark.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[China Danxia]] World Heritage Site\n*[[Candy Cane Mountains]]\n*[[Seven Coloured Earths]]\n\n==References==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web\n |script-title=zh:\u5f20\u6396\u4e39\u971e\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed\n |url=http://www.gsjw.gov.cn/content/2013-06/1493.html\n |trans-title=Zhangye Danxia National Geological Park\n |author=GSJW\n |publisher=Gansu Provincial Government\n |accessdate=12 September 2014\n |language=Chinese\n |date=2013-06-17\n |ref={{harvid|GSJW|2013}}\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=\u5f20\u6396\u4e39\u971e\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed\u51b0\u6c9f\u4e39\u971e\u666f\u533a\u6b63\u5f0f\u63ed\u724c\n |trans-title=Binggou Danxia Scenic Area of Zhangye Danxia National Geological Park inaugurated\n |url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20140804/41424689_0.shtml\n |first=Cao\n |last=Yong\n |publisher=Phoenix TV\n |language=Chinese\n |date=2014-08-04\n |ref={{harvid|Yong|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title=Picture gallery: Colourful rock formations in the Zhangye Danxia Landform Geological Park\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/picturegalleries/9550531/Colourful-rock-formations-in-the-Zhangye-Danxia-Landform-Geological-Park.html\n |first=Amos\n |last=Chapple\n |author2=Rex Features\n |publisher=Telegraph\n |accessdate=11 September 2014\n |ref={{harvid|Chapple|Rex|2014}}\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Zhangye|Zhangye National Geopark}}\n*[http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g1850955-d1857482-Reviews-Zhangye_Danxia_Geopark-Linze_County_Gansu.html Zhangye Danxia Geopark on TripAdvisor]\n\n{{Gansu topics}}\n\n[[Category:Geoparks in China]]\n[[Category:Geography of Gansu]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Gansu]]\n[[Category:Zhangye]]\n[[Category:Danxia landform]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area\n| name = Zhangye National Geopark<br/>{{nobold|{{lang|zh-hans|\u5f20\u6396\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed}}}}\n| iucn_category = \n| photo = File:Linze, Zhangye, Gansu, China - panoramio (4).jpg\n| photo_alt = \n| photo_caption = Badlands of the Zhangye National Geopark\n| photo_width = \n| map = China Gansu\n| map_alt = \n| map_caption = \n| map_width = \n| relief =\n| location = [[Linze County]] and [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan County]]\n| nearest_city = [[Zhangye]]\n| coordinates = {{coords|38|54|55.98|N|100|7|59.52|E|region:CN-62|display=inline, title}}\n| area = {{convert|322|km2|abbr=on}}\n| established = December 27, 2005 (as provincial geopark)\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = \n| website = \n}}\n\nThe '''Zhangye National Geopark''' ({{zh|s=\u5f20\u6396\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed |t=\u5f35\u6396\u570b\u5bb6\u5730\u8cea\u516c\u5712 |p=Zh\u0101ngy\u00e8 Gu\u00f3ji\u0101 D\u00eczh\u00ecg\u014dngyu\u00e1n}}) is located in [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan]] and [[Linze]] counties within the prefecture-level city of [[Zhangye]], in [[Gansu]], China.  It covers an area of {{convert|322|km2}}.  The site became a quasi-national geopark on April 23, 2012 (provisional name: '''Zhangye Danxia Geopark''').  It was formally designated as \"Zhangye National Geopark\" by the Ministry of Land and Resources on June 16, 2016 after it has passed the on-site acceptance test.  Known for its colorful rock formations, it has been voted by Chinese media outlets as one of the most beautiful landforms in China.\n\n==Location==\n[[File:Striated rocks in Zhangye National Geopark.jpg|thumb|left|Layers in the geopark]]\nThe park is located in the northern foothills of the [[Qilian Mountains]], in the counties of [[Linze County|Linze]] and [[Sunan Yugur Autonomous County|Sunan]], which are under the administration of the [[prefecture-level city]] of Zhangye, Gansu province. The main areas of [[Danxia landform]] are in Kangle and Baiyin townships.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}}\n\nThe core area of the park, Linze Danxia Scenic Area, is located {{convert|30|km}} west of downtown Zhangye and {{convert|20|km}} south of the seat of Linze County. It is the most developed and most visited part of the park.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}} A second scenic area, Binggou ({{lang|zh-hans|\u51b0\u6c9f}}), located on the north bank of Liyuan River ({{lang|zh-hans|\u68a8\u56ed\u6cb3}}), was officially inaugurated on 3 August 2014.{{sfn|Yong|2014}} Binggou covers an area of {{convert|300|km2}}, and its elevation ranges from 1,500 to 2,500 meters above sea level.{{sfn|Yong|2014}} A third area, Sunan Danxia Scenic Area, is located in Ganjun, south of Linze.\n\n==Landscape==\n[[File:Colorful strata (Zhangye National Geopark).jpg|thumb|right|Landscape of Zhangye National Geopark]]\nZhangye Danxia is known for the unusual colours of the rocks, which are smooth, sharp and several hundred meters tall. They are the result of deposits of [[sandstone]] and other minerals that occurred over 24 million years. The result (similar to a [[layer cake]]), was tilted by the action of the same tectonic plates responsible for creating parts of the [[Himalayan mountains]]. Wind, rain, and time then sculpted extraordinary shapes, including towers, pillars, and ravines, with varying colours, patterns, and sizes.{{sfn|Chapple|Rex|2014}}\n\n==Media and tourism==\nIn 2005, Zhangye Danxia was voted by a panel of reporters from 34 major media outlets as one of the most beautiful Danxia landform areas in China. In 2009, ''[[Chinese National Geography]]'' magazine chose Zhangye Danxia as one of the \"six most beautiful landforms\" in China.{{sfn|GSJW|2013}} The area has become a top tourist attraction for Zhangye. A series of boardwalks and access roads have been built to help visitors to explore the rock formations.{{sfn|Chapple|Rex|2014}} In 2014, 100 million yuan was invested to improve the facilities in the Binggou area.{{sfn|Yong|2014}}\n\nZhangye Danxia is '''featured''' as a natural wonder in the video game Sid Meier\u2019s [[Civilization VI]]. It was added in the Rise and Fall expansion.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"260px\" heights=\"230px\">\nBuildings in Zhangye National Geopark.jpg\nFlickr image 29851221553.jpg\nFlickr image 30483606125.jpg\nColourful mountains of the Zhangye National Geopark.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[China Danxia]] World Heritage Site\n*[[Candy Cane Mountains]]\n*[[Seven Coloured Earths]]\n\n==References==\n\n=== Notes ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\n* {{cite web\n |script-title=zh:\u5f20\u6396\u4e39\u971e\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed\n |url=http://www.gsjw.gov.cn/content/2013-06/1493.html\n |trans-title=Zhangye Danxia National Geological Park\n |author=GSJW\n |publisher=Gansu Provincial Government\n |accessdate=12 September 2014\n |language=Chinese\n |date=2013-06-17\n |ref={{harvid|GSJW|2013}}\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |title=\u5f20\u6396\u4e39\u971e\u56fd\u5bb6\u5730\u8d28\u516c\u56ed\u51b0\u6c9f\u4e39\u971e\u666f\u533a\u6b63\u5f0f\u63ed\u724c\n |trans-title=Binggou Danxia Scenic Area of Zhangye Danxia National Geological Park inaugurated\n |url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20140804/41424689_0.shtml\n |first=Cao\n |last=Yong\n |publisher=Phoenix TV\n |language=Chinese\n |date=2014-08-04\n |ref={{harvid|Yong|2014}}\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |title=Picture gallery: Colourful rock formations in the Zhangye Danxia Landform Geological Park\n |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/picturegalleries/9550531/Colourful-rock-formations-in-the-Zhangye-Danxia-Landform-Geological-Park.html\n |first=Amos\n |last=Chapple\n |author2=Rex Features\n |publisher=Telegraph\n |accessdate=11 September 2014\n |ref={{harvid|Chapple|Rex|2014}}\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{Wikivoyage|Zhangye|Zhangye National Geopark}}\n*[http://www.tripadvisor.com/Attraction_Review-g1850955-d1857482-Reviews-Zhangye_Danxia_Geopark-Linze_County_Gansu.html Zhangye Danxia Geopark on TripAdvisor]\n\n{{Gansu topics}}\n\n[[Category:Geoparks in China]]\n[[Category:Geography of Gansu]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Gansu]]\n[[Category:Zhangye]]\n[[Category:Danxia landform]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c5:e20a:7900:b85f:3c18:401c:8dd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhangye_National_Geopark"}
{"title_page": "Dominic Selwood", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Dominic Selwood\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|FRSA|FRHistS|size=100%}}\n| image = D Selwood DKS7.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|12|19|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = England\n| alma_mater = {{ubl | [[University of Oxford]] |  [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Pantheon-Sorbonne]] | [[University of Poitiers]] | [[University of Wales]] }}\n| occupation = {{hlist | [[Historian]] | [[author]] | [[journalist]] | [[barrister]]}}\n| genre = {{hlist | [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]] | historical fiction | non-fiction | history}}\n| notableworks = ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]'' (2013)\n| website ={{url|dominicselwood.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Dominic Selwood''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|FRSA|FRHistS}} (born 1970) is an English historian, journalist, author and barrister. He has written several works of history, historical fiction and historical thrillers, most notably ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]''. His background is in [[medieval history]].\n\n== Early life and career==\n\nSelwood was born on 19 December 1970<ref>http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n99002828.html</ref> in England, and grew up in [[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], in [[Cyprus]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=Crusaders in the Clouds: Dominic Selwood Explores Northern Cyprus (Author Guided Tour)|url=http://www.thebigthrill.org/2016/10/author-guided-tour-dominic-selwood-discovers-northern-cyprus/|website=The Big Thrill|publisher=International Thriller Writers|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> and in Germany. He went to school at [[Edge Grove School]] and [[Winchester College]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Wykeham Journal |url=http://www.joomag.com/magazine/wykeham-journal-2014/0352530001427817097?short |date=2014 |page=1 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> and studied law and French law at the [[University of Wales]].\n\nHe was awarded a scholarship to the [[Universit\u00e9 de Poitiers|University of Poitiers]], where a chance meeting in a local caf\u00e9 with the publisher (and early sponsor of ''[[Private Eye]]'')<ref>{{cite news |title=Anthony Blond, Obituary |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1580358/Anthony-Blond.html |publisher=The Daily Telepgraph |date=1 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barber |first1=Michael |title=Anthony Blond, Obituary |publisher=The Guardian |date=1 March 2008}}</ref> [[Anthony Blond]] led to a collaboration on ''Blond's Roman Emperors''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Blond |first=Anthony |title=Blond's Roman Emperors |year=1994 |publisher=Quartet Books |location=London |isbn=978-0704370029}}</ref> His doctoral research on medieval religious and military life, specialising in the [[Knights Templar]] and [[Knights Hospitaller]], the two leading [[Military order (society)|military orders]] of the [[Crusades]] was undertaken as a member of [[New College, Oxford]]. While conducting his research, he won a research scholarship to the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] in the history of [[Byzantium]] and the Christian Near-East. \n\nIn 1997, he was elected a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Historical Society]], and he is also a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London|Society of Antiquaries]] and a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]].\n\nHe was [[call to the bar|called to the Bar]] in London by [[Lincoln's Inn]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls to the bar: 10 October 1997 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/calls-to-the-bar-10-october-1997-1234997.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=29 September 2013 |location=London |date=10 October 1997}}</ref> joined a set of barristers' chambers in the [[Inner Temple]], and was a member of the Western Circuit.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=About|url=http://www.dominicselwood.com/about/|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> He is one of the founders of [[Arabesque Partners]].  In a 2014 interview he said that his work as a criminal [[barrister]] had been formative for writing thrillers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bilyeau |first1=Nancy |title=Dominic Selwood: Turning History Into Thrills |url=http://bloodygoodread.blogspot.co.uk/2014/08/dominic-selwood-turning-history-into.html?spref=tw |website=A Bloody Good Read}}</ref>\n\nSelwood says he is \"obsessed with the weirder side of the past\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ingram|title=Dominic Selwood (Interview, 11 February 2016)|url=http://marketing.ingramcontent.com/mrkng/2016/1107_4592/landingpage.html|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> and describes himself as a \"deeply fuzzy and laissez-faire English Catholic\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=Guy Fawkes, Islamists, converts, and terrorism: some things never change|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/11210864/Guy-Fawkes-Islamists-converts-and-terrorism-some-things-never-change.html|accessdate=22 January 2015|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=5 November 2014}}</ref> He has spoken at schools, universities, literary festivals and the British Museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magna Carta: Birth of Democracy or Historical Fantasy?|url=http://libertyleague.wix.com/llff15#!schedule/cjg9|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hampstead and Highgate Literary Festival|url=https://www.handhlitfest.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/HHLF_Brochure.pdf|accessdate=4 July 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=200 Years of the Elgin Collection|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/whats_on/events_calendar/event_detail.aspx?eventId=3040|publisher=British Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Classicism and nationalism: the Greek body in Enlightenment Europe|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/whats_on/events_calendar/event_detail.aspx?eventId=2032&title=Classicism+and+nationalism%3A+the+Greek+body+in+Enlightenment+Europe&eventType=Special+event|website=British Museum|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Journalism and media==\n\n=== Newspapers and magazines===\n\nSelwood writes for the UK's ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' newspaper and is currently a resident history columnist, including the daily 'On this Day' column.<ref>{{cite news|title=On this Day|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/authors/dominic-selwood/|accessdate=2 December 2016|publisher=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> His writing has been described as a \"must read\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coppen |first1=Luke |title=Must Reads |publisher=The Catholic Herald |date=23 May 2014}}</ref> \"a fascinating change from the usual dusty history books\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Lucianne.com|url=http://lucianne.com/thread/?artnum=778855|website=Lucianne.com|access-date=11 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715020545/http://lucianne.com/thread/?artnum=778855|archive-date=15 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and \"strident debunkery\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Magna Carta|journal=The Incorporated Council of Law Reporting for England and Wales|date=20 June 2014|url=http://www.iclr.co.uk/weekly-notes-legal-news-iclr-21-june-2014/}}</ref> He has also contributed to ''[[The Spectator]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[City_A.M.|CityAM]]'', ''[[Prospect Magazine]]'', and ''[[The Catholic Herald]]''.\n\n=== Television and radio===\n\nHe appears regularly on television and radio as a historical commentator and adviser, and on discussion shows like the [[BBC]]'s ''[[The Big Questions]]'' and Yesterday's Abandoned Engineering.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Works==\n\n=== Non-fiction===\n\n* ''Punctuation Without Tears: Punctuate Confidently - in Minutes!'', illustrated by Delia Johnson, (Corax, London, 2018) {{ISBN|978-0992633295}}, voted five stars by [[The Independent]] for putting simplicity and fun back into good writing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punctuation Without Tears by Dominic Selwood, book review: Puts simplicity and fun back into good writing |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/punctuation-without-tears-book-review-dominic-selwood-author-grammar-how-to-wri-a8482166.html |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> \n* ''Spies, Sadists and Sorcerers: The History You Weren't Taught at School'' (Crux Publishing, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-1909979338}}\n* ''Knights of the Cloister'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1999) {{ISBN|978-0851158280}}, a study of the medieval [[Knights Templar]] and [[Knights Hospitaller]], the first to deal in detail with their lives and activities in the south of France (their European headquarters), demonstrating how they raised the manpower, money and weapons to support the [[crusades]] in the East.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Berman|first=Constance|journal=Speculum|date=July 2001|volume=76|issue=3|pages=793\u2013795 |doi=10.2307/2903949 |title=Knights of the Cloister: Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania, c.1100-c.1300}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Nicholson |first=Helen |journal=English Historical Review |year=2000|volume=115 |issue=463 |pages=930\u2013931 |doi=10.1093/ehr/115.463.930 |title=Knights of the Cloister. Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania, 1100\u20131300 Dominic Selwood}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Abulafia|first=David|journal=American Historical Review|date=October 2002|volume=107|issue=4 |pages=1280\u20131281|doi=10.1086/532782|title=Reviews of Books:Knights of the Cloister: Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania c.1100-c.1300 Dominic Selwood}}</ref>\n\n=== Fiction===\n\n====Novels====\n* ''[[The Apocalypse Fire (novel)|The Apocalypse Fire]]'' (Canelo, London, 2016; Corax, London, 2016) {{ISBN|978-0992633271}}, a best-selling thriller described by the [[British Army]]'s official magazine as \"the best of [[James Bond]] and [[The Da Vinci Code]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Scott|title=Soldier Magazine (Official Magazine of the British Army)|url=http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/1e00a2a9#/1e00a2a9/64|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]'' (Corax, London, 2013; Canelo, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-0992633202}}, a best-selling thriller,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bilyeau|first1=Nancy |title=Dominic Selwood: Turning History Into Thrills|url=http://bloodygoodread.blogspot.co.uk/2014/08/dominic-selwood-turning-history-into.html|website=A Bloody Good Read}}</ref> voted Editor's 'Pick of the Week' by the ''[[Daily Express]]'' (7 February 2014) and one of 'The Five Best Religious Thrillers of All Time' by BestThrillers.com (3 December 2014).<ref>{{cite web |title=The Five Best Religious Thrillers of all Time |url=http://bestthrillers.com/best-thriller-lists/the-five-best-religious-thrillers-of-all-time |website=BestThrillers.com |accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Antiquarian Ghost Stories====\n* ''Suffer the Children'' (Corax, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-0992633233}}\n* ''The Voivod'' (Corax, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-0992633257}}\n\n== Films==\n\n* ''[[''Revelation'' (2001 film)|''Revelation'']]'', Cyclops Vision, starring [[Terence Stamp]], [[Udo Kier]], written and directed by [[Stuart Urban]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Revelation|title=British Film Institute|url=http://explore.bfi.org.uk/4ce2b85bc0c81|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Selwood|first=Dominic|title=Movies & TV|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/1590224/Dr-Dominic-Selwood|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Revelation (1991)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/263938/Revelation-Cyclops-Vision-Romulus-/overview|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> <!--why a list bullet here? needs a sentence-->\n\n== References==\n\n{{reflist|colwidth=28em}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.dominicselwood.com/ Official web site]\n* [http://www.dominicselwood.com/journalism/ Articles at ''The Telegraph'']\n* [http://bloodygoodread.blogspot.co.uk/2014/08/dominic-selwood-turning-history-into.html?spref=tw/ Author interview]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Selwood, Dominic}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Salisbury]]\n[[Category:People from Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Poitiers alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Inns of Court School of Law]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Historical Society]]\n[[Category:British medievalists]]\n[[Category:English historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:English thriller writers]]\n[[Category:Ghost story writers]]\n[[Category:British barristers]]\n[[Category:English male journalists]]\n[[Category:English bloggers]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:English male novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century British male writers]]\n[[Category:Male bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Dominic Selwood\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|FRSA|FRHistS|size=100%}}\n| image = D Selwood DKS7.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|12|19|df=yes}} \n| birth_place = England\n| alma_mater = {{ubl | [[University of Oxford]] |  [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Pantheon-Sorbonne]] | [[University of Poitiers]] | [[University of Wales]] }}\n| occupation = {{hlist | [[Historian]] | [[author]] | [[journalist]] | [[barrister]]}}\n| genre = {{hlist | [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]] | historical fiction | non-fiction | history}}\n| notableworks = ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]'' (2013)\n| website ={{url|dominicselwood.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Dominic Selwood''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FSA|FRSA|FRHistS}} (born 1970) is an English historian, journalist, author and barrister. He has written several works of history, historical fiction and historical thrillers, most notably ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]''. His background is in [[medieval history]].\n\n== Early life and career==\n\nSelwood was born on 19 December 1970<ref>http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n99002828.html</ref> in England, and grew up in [[Salisbury]], [[Wiltshire]], in [[Cyprus]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=Crusaders in the Clouds: Dominic Selwood Explores Northern Cyprus (Author Guided Tour)|url=http://www.thebigthrill.org/2016/10/author-guided-tour-dominic-selwood-discovers-northern-cyprus/|website=The Big Thrill|publisher=International Thriller Writers|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> and in Germany. He went to school at [[Edge Grove School]] and [[Winchester College]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Wykeham Journal |url=http://www.joomag.com/magazine/wykeham-journal-2014/0352530001427817097?short |date=2014 |page=1 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> and studied law and French law at the [[University of Wales]].\n\nHe was awarded a scholarship to the [[Universit\u00e9 de Poitiers|University of Poitiers]], where a chance meeting in a local caf\u00e9 with the publisher (and early sponsor of ''[[Private Eye]]'')<ref>{{cite news |title=Anthony Blond, Obituary |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1580358/Anthony-Blond.html |publisher=The Daily Telepgraph |date=1 March 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Barber |first1=Michael |title=Anthony Blond, Obituary |publisher=The Guardian |date=1 March 2008}}</ref> [[Anthony Blond]] led to a collaboration on ''Blond's Roman Emperors''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Blond |first=Anthony |title=Blond's Roman Emperors |year=1994 |publisher=Quartet Books |location=London |isbn=978-0704370029}}</ref> His doctoral research on medieval religious and military life, specialising in the [[Knights Templar]] and [[Knights Hospitaller]], the two leading [[Military order (society)|military orders]] of the [[Crusades]] was undertaken as a member of [[New College, Oxford]]. While conducting his research, he won a research scholarship to the [[Pantheon-Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] in the history of [[Byzantium]] and the Christian Near-East. \n\nIn 1997, he was elected a [[Fellow]] of the [[Royal Historical Society]], and he is also a Fellow of the [[Society of Antiquaries of London|Society of Antiquaries]] and a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]].\n\nHe was [[call to the bar|called to the Bar]] in London by [[Lincoln's Inn]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Calls to the bar: 10 October 1997 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/calls-to-the-bar-10-october-1997-1234997.html |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=29 September 2013 |location=London |date=10 October 1997}}</ref> joined a set of barristers' chambers in the [[Inner Temple]], and was a member of the Western Circuit.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=About|url=http://www.dominicselwood.com/about/|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> He is one of the founders of [[Arabesque Partners]].  In a 2014 interview he said that his work as a criminal [[barrister]] had been formative for writing thrillers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bilyeau |first1=Nancy |title=Dominic Selwood: Turning History Into Thrills |url=http://bloodygoodread.blogspot.co.uk/2014/08/dominic-selwood-turning-history-into.html?spref=tw |website=A Bloody Good Read}}</ref>\n\nSelwood says he is \"obsessed with the weirder side of the past\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ingram|title=Dominic Selwood (Interview, 11 February 2016)|url=http://marketing.ingramcontent.com/mrkng/2016/1107_4592/landingpage.html|accessdate=4 March 2016}}</ref> and describes himself as a \"deeply fuzzy and laissez-faire English Catholic\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Selwood|first1=Dominic|title=Guy Fawkes, Islamists, converts, and terrorism: some things never change|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/11210864/Guy-Fawkes-Islamists-converts-and-terrorism-some-things-never-change.html|accessdate=22 January 2015|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=5 November 2014}}</ref> He has spoken at schools, universities, literary festivals and the British Museum.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magna Carta: Birth of Democracy or Historical Fantasy?|url=http://libertyleague.wix.com/llff15#!schedule/cjg9|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hampstead and Highgate Literary Festival|url=https://www.handhlitfest.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/HHLF_Brochure.pdf|accessdate=4 July 2016}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=200 Years of the Elgin Collection|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/whats_on/events_calendar/event_detail.aspx?eventId=3040|publisher=British Museum}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Classicism and nationalism: the Greek body in Enlightenment Europe|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/whats_on/events_calendar/event_detail.aspx?eventId=2032&title=Classicism+and+nationalism%3A+the+Greek+body+in+Enlightenment+Europe&eventType=Special+event|website=British Museum|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Journalism and media==\n\n=== Newspapers and magazines===\n\nSelwood writes for the UK's ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' newspaper and is currently a resident history columnist, including the daily 'On this Day' column.<ref>{{cite news|title=On this Day|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/authors/dominic-selwood/|accessdate=2 December 2016|publisher=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> His writing has been described as a \"must read\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coppen |first1=Luke |title=Must Reads |publisher=The Catholic Herald |date=23 May 2014}}</ref> \"a fascinating change from the usual dusty history books\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Lucianne.com|url=http://lucianne.com/thread/?artnum=778855|website=Lucianne.com|access-date=11 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715020545/http://lucianne.com/thread/?artnum=778855|archive-date=15 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and \"strident debunkery\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Magna Carta|journal=The Incorporated Council of Law Reporting for England and Wales|date=20 June 2014|url=http://www.iclr.co.uk/weekly-notes-legal-news-iclr-21-june-2014/}}</ref> He has also contributed to ''[[The Spectator]]'', ''[[The Independent]]'', ''[[City_A.M.|CityAM]]'', ''[[Prospect Magazine]]'', and ''[[The Catholic Herald]]''.\n\n=== Television and radio===\n\nHe appears regularly on television and radio as a historical commentator and adviser, and on discussion shows like the [[BBC]]'s ''[[The Big Questions]]''.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Works==\n\n=== Non-fiction===\n\n* ''Punctuation Without Tears: Punctuate Confidently - in Minutes!'', illustrated by Delia Johnson, (Corax, London, 2018) {{ISBN|978-0992633295}}, voted five stars by [[The Independent]] for putting simplicity and fun back into good writing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Punctuation Without Tears by Dominic Selwood, book review: Puts simplicity and fun back into good writing |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/punctuation-without-tears-book-review-dominic-selwood-author-grammar-how-to-wri-a8482166.html |date=11 August 2018}}</ref> \n* ''Spies, Sadists and Sorcerers: The History You Weren't Taught at School'' (Crux Publishing, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-1909979338}}\n* ''Knights of the Cloister'' (The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1999) {{ISBN|978-0851158280}}, a study of the medieval [[Knights Templar]] and [[Knights Hospitaller]], the first to deal in detail with their lives and activities in the south of France (their European headquarters), demonstrating how they raised the manpower, money and weapons to support the [[crusades]] in the East.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Berman|first=Constance|journal=Speculum|date=July 2001|volume=76|issue=3|pages=793\u2013795 |doi=10.2307/2903949 |title=Knights of the Cloister: Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania, c.1100-c.1300}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Nicholson |first=Helen |journal=English Historical Review |year=2000|volume=115 |issue=463 |pages=930\u2013931 |doi=10.1093/ehr/115.463.930 |title=Knights of the Cloister. Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania, 1100\u20131300 Dominic Selwood}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Abulafia|first=David|journal=American Historical Review|date=October 2002|volume=107|issue=4 |pages=1280\u20131281|doi=10.1086/532782|title=Reviews of Books:Knights of the Cloister: Templars and Hospitallers in Central-Southern Occitania c.1100-c.1300 Dominic Selwood}}</ref>\n\n=== Fiction===\n\n====Novels====\n* ''[[The Apocalypse Fire (novel)|The Apocalypse Fire]]'' (Canelo, London, 2016; Corax, London, 2016) {{ISBN|978-0992633271}}, a best-selling thriller described by the [[British Army]]'s official magazine as \"the best of [[James Bond]] and [[The Da Vinci Code]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Scott|title=Soldier Magazine (Official Magazine of the British Army)|url=http://viewer.zmags.com/publication/1e00a2a9#/1e00a2a9/64|publisher=Ministry of Defence}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Sword of Moses (novel)|The Sword of Moses]]'' (Corax, London, 2013; Canelo, London, 2015) {{ISBN|978-0992633202}}, a best-selling thriller,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bilyeau|first1=Nancy |title=Dominic Selwood: Turning History Into Thrills|url=http://bloodygoodread.blogspot.co.uk/2014/08/dominic-selwood-turning-history-into.html|website=A Bloody Good Read}}</ref> voted Editor's 'Pick of the Week' by the ''[[Daily Express]]'' (7 February 2014) and one of 'The Five Best Religious Thrillers of All Time' by BestThrillers.com (3 December 2014).<ref>{{cite web |title=The Five Best Religious Thrillers of all Time |url=http://bestthrillers.com/best-thriller-lists/the-five-best-religious-thrillers-of-all-time |website=BestThrillers.com |accessdate=7 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Antiquarian Ghost Stories====